Subject: [R-meta] Negative Weights in a Multivariate Meta-Analysis
In-Reply-To: <ximss-17895818@n-cgpro-be-02.mail.uni-potsdam.de>
References: <ximss-17895818@n-cgpro-be-02.mail.uni-potsdam.de>
Message-ID: <69a106a3eee14ca89b109877c6e4263f@UM-MAIL3214.unimaas.nl>

Dear Martin,

In principle, res.1 is correct from a purely 'mathematical/statistical' perspective, but it's just very non-intuitive and I would also consider some other approach to avoid this issue.

As a sort-of compromise, you could use:

res.3 <- rma.mv(yi, V=V_list.1, W=1/(vi*rep(c(3,4), c(3,4))), method="FE", data=dat)
res.3

This uses inverse-variance weights that are adjusted based on the number of estimates within each study. That way, a study with many estimates would not overwhelm the other studies. In computing the standard error of the pooled estimate, this method still accounts for the dependency in the estimates via the V matrix.

Best,
Wolfgang

